## ğŸ·ï¸ Tagging and Pushing Custom Docker Images to Docker Hub

This section covers how to **tag Docker images correctly** and **push them to Docker Hub** so they can be shared, versioned, and deployed across environments.

## ğŸ§  Understanding Docker Image Tags (Why They Matter)

**Tags are:**
* Version control
* Safety rails
* Communication
All wrapped into a single label.

A **tag** points to a **specific version of an image**.

repository : tag
### Examples:
$ docker pull ubuntu:20.04
$ docker pull ubuntu:22.04

Both images exist side-by-side on your system.

### Default Behavior
If no tag is specified, Docker **silently uses**:
:latest


âš ï¸ `latest` does **not** mean stable or recommended. It simply means â€œthe default tag.â€


## ğŸ·ï¸ Assigning a Custom Tag to an Image
Tagging lets you rename or version an existing image so it can be pushed to a registry.

### Syntax
$ docker image tag <source_image> <repoUsername>/<newImageName>:<customTag>


### Example
$ docker image tag custom-ubuntu:1.0 pushcraft/custom-ubuntu:v1


### Verify the Tag
$ docker image ls


You will see **multiple tags pointing to the same IMAGE ID**.

---
## ğŸ§  Important Note:
âœ… **Tagging does NOT create a new image**
* Docker tags are **references (aliases)** to the same image ID
* A single image can have **multiple tags**

Example:
text
IMAGE ID        REPOSITORY               TAG
e3f1a9b2c7      custom-ubuntu            1.0
e3f1a9b2c7      pushcraft/custom-ubuntu  v1


Same image. Two names.

---

## ğŸš€ Pushing a Custom Image to Docker Hub

Once an image is tagged with your Docker Hub username, it can be pushed.

---

### ğŸ” 1. Log in to Docker Hub

$ docker login
You can authenticate using:
* Username + password
* Personal Access Token
* Web-based login flow

---

### ğŸ” 2. Confirm Image Name and Tag


$ docker images

Ensure the image name matches:
repoUsername/imageName:tag


Docker Hub **requires** this format.

---

### ğŸ“¤ 3. Push the Image
$ docker image push repoUsername/imageName:customTag


### Example


$ docker image push pushcraft/custom-ubuntu:v1

Docker uploads each image layer to Docker Hub.

example :
 $  docker image push kara101/kara101:tagX kara101/kara101:tagX
---

### âœ… 4. Verify on Docker Hub

* Log in to [https://hub.docker.com](https://hub.docker.com)
* Navigate to **Repositories**
* Confirm:
  * Image name
  * Tag
  * Push timestamp

---

## ğŸ§  Real-World Workflow (End-to-End)

text
docker commit â†’ docker tag â†’ docker push â†’ docker pull â†’ docker run


Used in:

* Team collaboration
* CI/CD pipelines
* Multi-environment deployments
* Kubernetes clusters

---

## âš ï¸ Best Practices (Production Mindset)

âœ” Use **explicit version tags**
âœ” Avoid `latest` in production
âœ” Use semantic versioning:

text
1.0.0 â†’ 1.0.1 â†’ 1.1.0 â†’ 2.0.0


âœ” Keep tags meaningful:
text
myapp:1.2-alpine
myapp:1.2-slim


---

## ğŸ§¾ Summary

* Tags are **labels**, not copies
* One image can have **many tags**
* Docker Hub requires:
  username/image:tag
  
* Tagging enables **versioning, rollback, and sharing**
* Pushing makes images **portable across systems**

